he experiences of many writers-music and art critics, authors of self-help books, poets, and philosophers-to explore the transformative power of the experience of art. In a concluding chapter on the educational relevance of Dewey's views, the author focuses on two instances of flawed educational practice, showing how a more conscientious application of Dewey's view of the arts could have improved the learning experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAesthetics, American. 0aAesthetics, Moderny19th century. 0aAesthetics, Moderny20th century. 0aAesthetics, Modern. 0aArtxStudy and teaching. 7aEDUCATION / Teaching Methods & Materials / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030007213640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014770440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147704423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300147704/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY